				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: We don't separate genders
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1750980">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Atelen</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1750967#post1750967" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Well, at least the first page was an interesting discussion. Even if I don't agree with everything you've said, Gol, thanks for giving me some things to ponder about.<br />
<br />
To run with a point, I don't quite understand how Gniz (and kaisann?) think that gender is just this arbitrary construct that (choosing my words with some care) could be changed if all of a sudden everyone started thinking about things differently. Or, more accurately, I don't understand how this viewpoint differs at all from saying, for example, &quot;Well, if only everyone decided that murder was wrong, we'd stop having murder!&quot; Whether or not you believe in gender as a binary or spectrum or whatever (I tend to lean towards the spectrum idea), Gol's stance that gender and gender roles are deeply rooted in the biological and psychological make-up of the human race is pretty straightforward. X thousand years of evolution tend to lay down some pretty persistent patterns of thought. Not that some of those patterns can't and shouldn't be changed; don't think I'm trying to make a, &quot;Well it's biology so we can't rise above it&quot; argument here.<br />
<br />
Now, please correct me if I'm wrong, but your point is that, given current technology, understanding of the human mind, etc. etc. we should be able to just shake all that past programming off? Snap of the fingers, so long standard social &quot;norms&quot;? Does that honestly seem realistic to you? Or am I missing a point you're trying to make? (Not that some of those patterns can't and shouldn't be changed; don't think I'm trying to make a, &quot;Well it's biology so we can't rise above it&quot; argument here.)<br />
<br />
Assuming I'm missing at least some portion of what you're shooting for: Would it be closer to say that society too often ties up too much of an individual's gender with their physical sex in terms of determining what role(s) an individual is able to fill and still be seen as &quot;normal&quot;?<br />
<br />
Edit: I had a lot more typed out, but I want to get onto the same page with folks before I go making points.<br />
<br />
PS - Not to be the chorus here Gol, but Delores makes a decent point. If you feel that strongly it's better to say nothing than to respond in &lt;insert emotion&gt; and lose some of the credibility of the so-far open and civil (mostly) discussion. On the other hand, I think it's fair that kaisann's first comment was a little abrasive; unless you can argue that 20-something women <i>don't</i> have to fend off an inundating wave of male attention?</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I did not mean to give the impression that current gender roles have no root in biology. I am arguing that the biological necessity has been removed via scientific advances. While it would be nice to if it were as simple as a snap of the fingers I am not so dumb as to think it is possible. Your final statement more or less accurately summarizes my personal stance. With lots of luck we might see this society sometime in our lives, but I highly doubt it. I fail to see any harm in pushing towards it though.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
