			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: We don't separate genders
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1750988">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Goladus</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1750929#post1750929" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Kaisann did not enter the discussion to participate in good faith.  The first thing he did was project his cynical bitterness on me in response to a comment he clearly failed to understand.  He is even proud of this. <br />
<br />
I would urge others to note whether his approach is dogmatic or open-minded, whether he is willing to listen and accept other's valid points, whether he makes any effort to avoid fallacy, and whether his words really reflect reality as it exists instead of the reality they want to believe.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>And Goladus goes for the reversal! A for effort, but unfortunately a bit too light on substance to be convincing.  <br />
<br />
I'm largely content to let others come to a decision based on the content of our multiple conversations on this and related topics.  One quick note on my entry to this thread, however: the post that you assert I &quot;clearly failed to understand&quot; is a post where you described the experiences of &quot;men&quot; and &quot;women&quot; as if your specific experience as a cisgendered, heterosexual male, and your obviously skewed perception of the experiences of cisgendered, heterosexual women, applies broadly enough to make the generalizations you did.  It's worth noting (for those who may not remember the multiple page conversation I had with Goladus a few months back) that one point I've made repeatedly in my interactions with you is that while your framing of gender is convenient for your rhetoric, it totally fails to actually capture the diversity of human experience as it relates to gender presentation, sexuality, etc.  I'll leave the question of whether my description of your comments (i.e. coming from &quot;bitter, pedantic guy who doesn't let things go and has had a few too many bad experiences with women&quot;) is more accurate than your description of mine (i.e. &quot;cynical bitterness&quot;) to anyone who still cares about this exchange <img src="images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Wink" class="inlineimg" /><br />
<br />
Having said all that, I would hate to have personalities distract from the fact that your arguments are, at best, very problematic.  I'll give a quick example.  In every thread on this and related topics, you keep charging forward, often making fascinating but pretty much meaningless comments like &quot;Our incredible success and prosperity shouldn't obscure the reality that traditional masculine virtues are still important.&quot; <br />
<br />
Did anyone argue that &quot;traditional masculine virtues&quot; are unimportant, Goladus?  Or did you come to the conclusion (based on thin to no evidence) that people who argue that gender is largely socially constructed, or that gender is a continuum automatically reject traditional masculine values?  You started out this thread by stating the following:<br />
<br />
&quot;Because of the feminist obsession with patriarchy and eliminating systemic subordination, they have gone through great lengths to stamp out any notion that men should lead their girlfriends.&quot;<br />
<br />
There's a lot of bullshit to unpack there, but underlying your comment is clearly the idea that it's a <i>bad thing</i> that a lot of people believe that men should not lead their girlfriends, that negative things have come from that change, and that feminists are to blame for it.  It's not difficult to draw a straight line from this comment to your later comment about &quot;traditional masculine values&quot; - basically, your entire line of argument is pretty clearly a manifestation of &quot;men are under attack (and holy shit we should care).&quot;  Why is this type of argument problematic?  <i>Because cisgendered men possess privilege with respect to everyone else</i>. As <a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?72750-Owning-your-S**t-one-woman-s-quest-for-gender-equality&amp;p=1724059&amp;viewfull=1#post1724059" target="_blank">&quot;painfully obvious&quot; as the erosion of your may privilege may be to you</a>, you still possess a significant amount of privilege with respect to women <img src="images/smilies/frown.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Frown" class="inlineimg" />  Taking into account other axes of oppression, you possess privilege with respect to pretty much everyone else who isn't a cisgendered, heterosexual, white male.  <br />
<br />
As I've said to you many, many times, I'd love to work with you to gradually erode the narratives that underlie male privilege, het privilege and cisgender privilege to the benefit of everyone.  Instead, you insist on having a laser focus on things like how it's horrible that there's &quot;<a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?72750-Owning-your-S**t-one-woman-s-quest-for-gender-equality&amp;p=1724425&amp;viewfull=1#post1724425" target="_blank">a lack of an accepted male gender role</a>.&quot;  Unsurprisingly, my solution to that &quot;issue&quot; is not to support a system that polices compliance with the gender binary since that would be directly counter-productive to my work to erode the narratives about what constitutes &quot;male&quot; and &quot;female&quot; behavior (and that ultimately disadvantage both men and women).<br />
<br />
I continue to be an activist because attitudes and arguments like yours are genuinely problematic, Gol, and while male privilege exists, feminist activism and gender activism will both remain necessary.  Have a great day.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
