		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: We don't separate genders
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1750997">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Atelen</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1750967#post1750967" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">To run with a point, I don't quite understand how Gniz (and kaisann?) think that gender is just this arbitrary construct that (choosing my words with some care) could be changed if all of a sudden everyone started thinking about things differently.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I haven't spent much time in this thread laying out my position on the topic of gender, so I can see how you might reach this conclusion.  My point isn't that gender is an arbitrary construct, not least because narratives around gender provide the basis for male, heterosexual and cisgender privilege.  You can read more on my position <a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?62379-Gender-stuffs&amp;p=1450793&amp;viewfull=1#post1450793" target="_blank">here</a> and <a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?62379-Gender-stuffs&amp;p=1450888&amp;viewfull=1#post1450888" target="_blank">here</a>, but the gist is that gender is already a continuum and primarily performative in nature.  As things stand, no one (or almost no one) 100% embodies &quot;feminine&quot; or &quot;masculine,&quot; although the majority of people do currently strongly identify with one gender or the other.  For that reason, I support individuals who are comfortable conforming to the gender binary just as much as individuals who are not, but I work towards eroding the narratives that underlie various types of privilege because of the impact that privilege has on oppressed groups.  For example, male privilege is underlied by a number of narratives about what constitutes &quot;male&quot; characteristics and behaviors and &quot;female&quot; characteristics and behaviors - I work to erode those narratives because male privilege primarily harms women.  Male privilege also harms men (see, e.g., narratives around women being better parents), but this is really a secondary effect.  Fortunately, this isn't a zero-sum game - by working to erode those narratives, we're actually ultimately helping everyone!<br />
<br />
Now, this type of work absolutely takes time - no one is going to flip a switch and magically find that male privilege has disappeared.  The point is that these roles are at best tenuously tied to biology (which is one of Goladus' main talking points).  I bring up Goladus here because the primary reason I take part in threads like these is that MRA rhetoric like his proceeds from the (privileged) belief that male privilege has already been eroded to a point where some sort of correction is necessary.  I think you can see pretty clearly in his comments a desire for a return traditional notions of manhood and male behavior, which is interesting given that traditional notions of manhood and male behavior are still firmly entrenched.  You can also see Goladus explicitly pushing back when people have indicated they feel constrained by narratives surrounding male behavior (e.g. Gniz).  There are many reasons I find his arguments so problematic, but hopefully that helps contextualize things a bit.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Atelen</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1750967#post1750967" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">On the other hand, I think it's fair that kaisann's first comment was a little abrasive; unless you can argue that 20-something women <i>don't</i> have to fend off an inundating wave of male attention?</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Goladus made a generalization without nuance - everyone's experience is <i>like this</i>.  I know many cisgendered men whose dating experiences was much more like his description of a mid-20s woman's experience, and vice versa.  I also know a decent number of transgendered women, and I'm sure you will not be surprised to learn that their experiences are nothing like his description.  Perhaps this inability to account for more than what appears to be a very narrow range of experience may be due to his previous assertions that &quot;<a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?72750-Owning-your-S**t-one-woman-s-quest-for-gender-equality&amp;p=1724039&amp;viewfull=1#post1724039" target="_blank">transgendered women aren't considered women because the vast majority of cisgendered men don't see them as women</a>.&quot;  But what about homosexual men and women?  My take is that his inability is due to a persistent blind spot in his analyses. There are many, many individuals who do not conform to traditional definitions of gender and sexuality, and he pretty much never tries to take their widely varying experiences into account.<br />
<br />
Even if we accept the premise for the sake of argument, what does it mean?  Is there something inherent to cisgendered women that creates this dynamic?  Further, is this a dynamic that benefits anyone?  The very gender roles that result in perceptions like &quot;women in their mid-20s have to deal with an onslaught of male attention while for men dating starts out rough&quot; are the ones that Goladus is arguing in favor of.<br />
<br />
I'll stop there - does that explanation make sense?  Let me know if you have any questions!
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
