		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: We don't separate genders
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1751007">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Gnizmo</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1750987#post1750987" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Too vague for me to really weigh in on. So long as the roles are sufficiently broad, or are only present in any real sense when they are necessary it would be fine I suppose. The crucial part is for anyone to be able to be whatever the hell they are so long as it does not actually harm anyone else.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Fair enough. I took it as, basically, a thought exercise. If concepts like &quot;alpha male&quot; or &quot;stay at home mom&quot; or what have you still existed, only devoid of connection to physical sex, would there still be an uprising against... well, &quot;the patriarchy&quot; doesn't fit anymore. My point being, the divisiveness in the debate on sex and gender seems to be that society as a whole, and people in the dominant, powerful roles, tend to assign an individual's &quot;proper&quot; place by their physical sex, not their gender/sense-of-self (recall I tend to use gender as what you self-define as, versus sex is physical body shape).<br />
<br />
To attempt a better phrasing, I think part of the debate here is that there is a difference between re-defining societal roles/norms to not include a context of an individual's physical sex (keep the structure of society, do away with concept that physical characteristics determine place in structure), and trying to do away/completely re-work that structure. Of course, those with a vested interest in *not* changing society either way find it easier to hide themselves as the first option, but that's another story.<br />
<br />
So, completely switching gears for a second, I wanted to ask an open question (but directed to kaisann because I'm curious about his/her opinion) about a discussion I had with a friend the other day. A man sees a woman from across a room, and instantly notices how attractive she is to him. Due to this fact, he decides to go strike up a conversation with her; his first comment is specifically, &quot;Hey there, you are looking exceptionally pretty tonight.&quot; (Or something similar. A direct comment on her attractiveness).<br />
<br />
A) Was he being objectifying in this context and was it right or wrong, and B) if he wasn't, what would have pushed him over the line/where is the line.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
		        		<blockquote class="signature restore"><div class="signaturecontainer"><span style="font-family: Arial Black"><i><font color="#2F4F4F">~ Breathe Deep, Seek Peace ~</font></i></span></div></blockquote>
				
                                        
			</div>
			
