			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: We don't separate genders
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1751012">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>kaisann</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1750997#post1750997" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">I haven't spent much time in this thread laying out my position on the topic of gender, so I can see how you might reach this conclusion.  My point isn't that gender is an arbitrary construct, not least because narratives around gender provide the basis for male, heterosexual and cisgender privilege.  You can read more on my position <a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?62379-Gender-stuffs&amp;p=1450793&amp;viewfull=1#post1450793" target="_blank">here</a> and <a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?62379-Gender-stuffs&amp;p=1450888&amp;viewfull=1#post1450888" target="_blank">here</a>, but the gist is that gender is already a continuum and primarily performative in nature.  As things stand, no one (or almost no one) 100% embodies &quot;feminine&quot; or &quot;masculine,&quot; although the majority of people do currently strongly identify with one gender or the other.  For that reason, I support individuals who are comfortable conforming to the gender binary just as much as individuals who are not, but I work towards eroding the narratives that underlie various types of privilege because of the impact that privilege has on oppressed groups.  For example, male privilege is underlied by a number of narratives about what constitutes &quot;male&quot; characteristics and behaviors and &quot;female&quot; characteristics and behaviors - I work to erode those narratives because male privilege primarily harms women.  Male privilege also harms men (see, e.g., narratives around women being better parents), but this is really a secondary effect.  Fortunately, this isn't a zero-sum game - by working to erode those narratives, we're actually ultimately helping everyone!</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Thanks for the context, and I'll be happy to re-read things when I'm not heading out for a social thing. Since I don't have the time to go into detail right now (and I really want to take the time to choose my language without putting my foot in my mouth), I'll re-ask what I asked Gniz up above; do you see the content of the narratives of themselves as wrong/harmful, or the fact that they are applied unfairly and based strictly on physical sexual characteristics? For example, if some (physically) males were accepted as belonging the female narrative and vice versa. Are the narratives something that have grains of substance to them and need to be re-worked, or something that should be done away with entirely? Or at base: How would you look to construct new narratives, assuming you believe we need new ones to replace our current ones?<br />
<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>kaisann</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1750997#post1750997" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Goladus made a generalization without nuance - everyone's experience is <i>like this</i>.  I know many cisgendered men whose dating experiences was much more like his description of a mid-20s woman's experience, and vice versa.  I also know a decent number of transgendered women, and I'm sure you will not be surprised to learn that their experiences are nothing like his description.  Perhaps this inability to account for more than what appears to be a very narrow range of experience may be due to his previous assertions that &quot;<a href="http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?72750-Owning-your-S**t-one-woman-s-quest-for-gender-equality&amp;p=1724039&amp;viewfull=1#post1724039" target="_blank">transgendered women aren't considered women because the vast majority of cisgendered men don't see them as women</a>.&quot;  But what about homosexual men and women?  My take is that his inability is due to a persistent blind spot in his analyses. There are many, many individuals who do not conform to traditional definitions of gender and sexuality, and he pretty much never tries to take their widely varying experiences into account.<br />
<br />
Even if we accept the premise for the sake of argument, what does it mean?  Is there something inherent to cisgendered women that creates this dynamic?  Further, is this a dynamic that benefits anyone?  The very gender roles that result in perceptions like &quot;women in their mid-20s have to deal with an onslaught of male attention while for men dating starts out rough&quot; are the ones that Goladus is arguing in favor of.<br />
<br />
I'll stop there - does that explanation make sense?  Let me know if you have any questions!</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Fair enough; it was a generalization. I have more questions to continue this point of conversation, but I must run, so do remind me to re-open it again later.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
