		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: We don't separate genders
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1751024">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Atelen</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1751007#post1751007" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">To attempt a better phrasing, I think part of the debate here is that there is a difference between re-defining societal roles/norms to not include a context of an individual's physical sex (keep the structure of society, do away with concept that physical characteristics determine place in structure), and trying to do away/completely re-work that structure.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>One of the sticking points I have with that framing is that I'm never really sure what a given person really means when they say things like &quot;do away with societal norms.&quot;  My position is that insisting on sticking with, for example, traditional notions of masculinity and femininity will only harm everyone in both the short and long term.  Societal norms demand adherence to the gender binary.  If our desired end state is one where no one is constrained to perform their assigned gender, one necessary step is to eliminate those societal norms.  But by definition, that change can only happen gradually so I'm not really sure why anyone is particularly concerned.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Atelen</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1751007#post1751007" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">So, completely switching gears for a second, I wanted to ask an open question (but directed to kaisann because I'm curious about his/her opinion) about a discussion I had with a friend the other day.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Absent some context that would render it inappropriate (e.g. most work functions, a funeral, the guy in question is actually intending to rape the woman in question) almost no one would argue that the (presumably cisgendered) male in your scenario crossed a line in making that type of comment.  <br />
<br />
There is some nuance here, however.  There are a fair number of women who experience being catcalled (etc.) on a daily basis.  Male privilege being what it is, it's all too easy to dismiss the impact of being subjected to that type of treatment on a consistent basis - one fairly common MRA response to feminist objections to, e.g., men catcalling women is that <a href="http://www.amptoons.com/blog/2010/08/30/cartoon-street-harassment/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">they would love to be catcalled</a>!  That's why, as an activist, I typically ask cisgendered men to check their privilege.  It does not mean &quot;being subservient to women&quot; or any similar bullshit that you may have seen elsewhere on the internet.  It mean taking a step beyond &quot;no means no&quot; (which puts literally all the responsibility on an oppressed group) and considering how one's actions might be interpreted in light of the enormous privilege possessed by cisgendered men with respect to cisgendered women.  In general, however, I don't think I'd argue that a single off-hand comment is enough to cross a line.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
		        		<blockquote class="signature restore"><div class="signaturecontainer">Kai`ili`i ho'omake`akauao i`a</div></blockquote>
				
                                        
			</div>
			
