				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: We don't separate genders
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1751026">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Atelen</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1751012#post1751012" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">I'll re-ask what I asked Gniz up above; do you see the content of the narratives of themselves as wrong/harmful, or the fact that they are applied unfairly and based strictly on physical sexual characteristics?</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>My position is that perpetuation of the narratives that underlie various forms of privilege is experienced by oppressed groups as oppression.  These narratives do directly and indirectly harm pretty much everyone, although it's also clear in which direction the power dynamics I describe as privilege run.  In my view, eroding those narratives is ultimately the only way to also erode the impact that privilege has on our lives.  See...<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Atelen</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1751012#post1751012" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">For example, if some (physically) males were accepted as belonging the female narrative and vice versa. Are the narratives something that have grains of substance to them and need to be re-worked, or something that should be done away with entirely? Or at base: How would you look to construct new narratives, assuming you believe we need new ones to replace our current ones?</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>...in a sense, the narratives I'm referring to are unfairly applied to pretty much everyone - no one actually embodies all of them.  The fun part of these conversations is that the narratives in question often apply to a lot of people!  This is a primary cause of one of the major issues with the gender binary: relevant narratives don't universally apply <i>but people act like they do</i>.  I believe that we're constantly constructing new narratives, and that people will come to accept organically both that gender is a continuum and that this is a good thing.  The sooner we get away from the idea that enforced adherence to the gender binary is a good thing, the better off we'll be.  Whether that means society ultimately recognizes several very broad categories or takes another approach is an open question.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
