			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: We don't separate genders
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1751039">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Atelen</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1750967#post1750967" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Well, at least the first page was an interesting discussion. Even if I don't agree with everything you've said, Gol, thanks for giving me some things to ponder about.<br />
<br />
To run with a point, I don't quite understand how Gniz (and kaisann?) think that gender is just this arbitrary construct that (choosing my words with some care) could be changed if all of a sudden everyone started thinking about things differently. Or, more accurately, I don't understand how this viewpoint differs at all from saying, for example, &quot;Well, if only everyone decided that murder was wrong, we'd stop having murder!&quot; Whether or not you believe in gender as a binary or spectrum or whatever (I tend to lean towards the spectrum idea), Gol's stance that gender and gender roles are deeply rooted in the biological and psychological make-up of the human race is pretty straightforward. X thousand years of evolution tend to lay down some pretty persistent patterns of thought. Not that some of those patterns can't and shouldn't be changed; don't think I'm trying to make a, &quot;Well it's biology so we can't rise above it&quot; argument here.<br />
<br />
Now, please correct me if I'm wrong, but your point is that, given current technology, understanding of the human mind, etc. etc. we should be able to just shake all that past programming off? Snap of the fingers, so long standard social &quot;norms&quot;? Does that honestly seem realistic to you? Or am I missing a point you're trying to make? (Not that some of those patterns can't and shouldn't be changed; don't think I'm trying to make a, &quot;Well it's biology so we can't rise above it&quot; argument here.)</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>That is not what the statement &quot;gender is a social construct&quot; means, no. It is a very real thing, but most of what it means to be male or female is defined by society and essentially imprinted on people as they grow up in that society. The point is that what it means to be &quot;male&quot; or &quot;female&quot; doesn't <i>really </i>have all that much to do with one's actual physical sex. Being something that is impressed upon people by society, yes, changing how a society as a whole thinks about gender can change how the genders are defined, and that is something that we ought to be interested in doing, because as things stand now the relative rigidity of the gender binary is very damaging to a lot of (or possibly even most) people. <br />
<br />
(Disclaimer: It's been a while since I took classes relating to this, so my explanation may not be as clear as I would like it to be.)
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
