		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: We don't separate genders
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1751665">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							&quot;Gender as a social construct&quot; can be useful for <i>analysis</i> of society and culture.  Basically, you purposely set aside preconceptions about &quot;physical sex&quot; and look at the roles people fill and how they interact with society.  You might observe a &quot;male pop singer&quot; and a &quot;female pop singer&quot;, ignore the sex of the performers, and analyze the appearance, behavior and perception of each one and it's role in society.<br />
<br />
Believe it or not I think this is a worthwhile model to explore.  But there are two major pitfalls.  <br />
<br />
The first is what we've seen here in this thread, which is taking a concept meant to be an analytical tool and interpreting it to mean that biological sex and intuitive, self-organizing behavior has nothing to do with the resulting gendered norms, that it's all just &quot;culture&quot; and &quot;society.&quot;  Furthermore, there's usually an unspoken assumption &quot;we&quot; can &quot;change&quot; society, without being too explicit about what those changes should be or who should change them.  So long as they're moving towards the ideal of &quot;no gendered norms at all&quot; that counts as progressive.  That's what I find dangerously ignorant, even when it's not glaringly hypocritical.<br />
<br />
Consider female athletes.  If we did not have a separate gender role for female athletes, people born with vaginas would not be able to play professional sports; and based on the number of female athletes in the world, I would say that having a gender role for female athletes is far preferable than just doing away with sports entirely, because it's an inherently male-biased activity.  Doing away with sports entirely is a real sentiment, I'm sure you've seen it even here on the forums.  But I think you would agree that if we're going to dismantle all sports everywhere, there should be a better reason than a nebulous idea of gender equality.<br />
<br />
The second is that not everything is a &quot;role&quot; and not every role is inherently gendered.  Society may request/demand any number of roles (factory worker, soldier, writer, politician, mother) and some of them become dominated by one sex for any number of reasons, including that the sex is best equipped to take on that role.  During WW2, factory worker was a woman's role while soldier was a man's role.  The uniforms and tools used by the men and women filling those roles were primarily geared towards performing the necessary role and not fulfilling a gender narrative for the sake of an individual.  Soldiers wore helmets because they helped win the war on the front lines, not because it's a sexy thing for a man to wear.  It only becomes a true gender symbol when the vaginas in society tingle and moisten for the soldiers wearing those helmets while at the same time drying up for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Captain_America" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">4-F rejects</a>.  It's true that women were (and still are) excluded from infantry, so it was a gender role in the sense that only men were selected to fill it, but to a large extent the social penalties for failing to fill an expected male role were <i>sexual</i>.  Many 4-F men, seen as lower status, were often at a disadvantage with potential mates.<br />
<br />
And for the girl's part, when it came time to attract a man she took off the overalls and put on a pretty dress, because men are biologically predisposed to be attracted to beauty, delicacy, and other &quot;feminine&quot; traits.<br />
<br />
In modern society, there are fewer necessary roles and great prosperity.  Society is much bigger, much more complex, and much less restrictive.  In the absence of important roles to fill, is it any wonder that sexual-based roles are becoming more prevalent?  Instead of setting aside the overalls and putting on a pretty dress to attract men, women are spending as much as possible to make themselves as attractive as possible.  A lot of what might seem like &quot;society impressing&quot; is really emergent sexual dynamics in a culture where there are no important gendered roles (or at least, many don't believe there are any important gender roles, such as &quot;father&quot;).
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
		<div class="postfoot">
