		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: We don't separate genders
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1751757">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Goladus</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1751665#post1751665" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">The first is what we've seen here in this thread, which is taking a concept meant to be an analytical tool and interpreting it to mean that biological sex and intuitive, self-organizing behavior has nothing to do with the resulting gendered norms, that it's all just &quot;culture&quot; and &quot;society.&quot; Furthermore, there's usually an unspoken assumption &quot;we&quot; can &quot;change&quot; society, without being too explicit about what those changes should be or who should change them.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Your use of terminology is a bit confused so it's probably a good idea to start there.  When we talk about gender roles, we're invoking language that is intended to describe the behavior of &quot;men&quot; and &quot;women&quot; whether or not the individuals in each bucket conform to expectations for their gender.  You've provided a couple of great examples in your post, e.g. &quot;men are biologically predisposed to be attracted to beauty, delicacy, and other 'feminine' traits.&quot;  Separately, individuals belong to any number of different &quot;roles,&quot; many of which are gendered to a significant degree.  Gendered &quot;roles&quot; are considered gendered due in large part to the narratives that underlie male privilege (which is inextricably linked to traditional gender roles!).  As I've said previously, I work to erode those narratives because they directly and indirectly harm pretty much everyone.  <br />
<br />
The position I take is that what you perceive to be &quot;intuitive, self-organizing behavior&quot; is to a significant extent determined by society, not that &quot;biological sex has nothing to do with gendered norms.&quot;  Having said that, the ideal I work towards is a society where individuals are not constrained to perform their assigned gender.  That means, in part, eroding narratives that raise barriers to participation by women and men in various activities and fields.  It means eroding narratives that implicitly or explicitly define &quot;appropriate&quot; behaviors and activities for women and men.  It means recognizing that individuals will always have their own strengths and interests, and that it's ultimately beneficial to society for everyone to have the freedom to pursue their own interests and leverage their individual strengths.  &quot;Courage,&quot; &quot;beauty,&quot; &quot;physical strength,&quot; &quot;ability at math,&quot; &quot;parenting skills,&quot; etc. are not gendered traits, they are individual traits - the sooner we collectively realize this, the better.<br />
<br />
I'm hoping you can say more about &quot;sexual-based roles...becoming more prevalent,&quot; because I'm not sure that your assertion makes sense.  I do want to spend a bit of time unpacking your final sentence, however.  First, it is still the case that the &quot;important&quot; (from a broad social perspective) &quot;roles&quot; are overwhelmingly gendered, and overwhelmingly populated by men.  Second, I understand from your posting history how crappy a situation you believe fathers to be in, but I don't think it's particularly fair to say that &quot;father&quot; is any less important a role than &quot;mother&quot; (again, from a broad social perspective).  Having said that, stay-at-home fathers, fathers involved in custody battles, etc. are all victims of some of the narratives that underlie male privilege.  Help me erode those narratives!  It won't make &quot;father&quot; a more &quot;important&quot; gendered &quot;role,&quot; but it will help us move toward a society where stay-at-home fathers are not stigmatized for pursuing their interests and leveraging their strengths.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
		        		<blockquote class="signature restore"><div class="signaturecontainer">Kai`ili`i ho'omake`akauao i`a</div></blockquote>
				
                                        
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
